 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">(i) In the case of N = 3 we have systematically improved the initial conditions obtained from solutions of the linearized eom and obtained numerical solutions that are rather close to exact spin waves, see section, 4.3: #aaa5f04s4-3</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">(ii) In the special case of vanishing wave number k = 0 it is possible to obtain analytical solutions that describe &apos;synchronized oscillations&apos;, see section, 5: #aaa5f04s5. It would be surprising if such exact spin waves exist for k = 0 but not for larger k</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">(iii) In the limit of N\longrightarrow \infty, i.e. for the dipole chain, exact spin waves exist with arbitrary amplitudes, see section, 6: #aaa5f04s6. Again, it would be surprising if such exact spin waves exist for N\longrightarrow \infty but not for finite N</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
